@page "/"

<PageTitle>Home</PageTitle>

<h1>Hello, world!</h1>

<p>
    Welcome to the <strong>Blazor Contracts</strong> demo app. This is the default
    Blazor Web App template (Home, Counter, Weather) wired up to use the
    <a href="https://github.com/Kanawanagasaki/Kanawanagasaki.BlazorContracts" target="_blank">Kanawanagasaki.BlazorContracts</a>
    library, with <strong>prerendering</strong>, <strong>SignalR (InteractiveServer)</strong>,
    and <strong>WebAssembly</strong> all enabled.
</p>

<h2>What this demo shows</h2>

<p>
    The same Razor component code runs in three different render contexts. The
    Blazor Contracts library's <code>IContractsService</code> is resolved from DI,
    and the source generators swap the implementation automatically:
</p>

<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Prerendering (server static SSR)</strong> - the page is rendered
        on the server before the response is sent. The server-side
        <code>ContractsService</code> invokes the handler directly in-process.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>InteractiveServer (SignalR)</strong> - the page is interactive
        over a WebSocket. Still uses the server-side
        <code>ContractsService</code> and invokes handlers in-process.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>InteractiveWebAssembly</strong> - the page is rendered inside
        the browser using WebAssembly. The client-side
        <code>ClientContractsService</code> sends HTTP requests back to the
        auto-mapped endpoints (registered via <code>app.MapContracts()</code>),
        which then invoke the same handlers.
    </li>
</ul>
